 gaining traction in the pastries market, as consumers seek out more wholesome and nutritious alternatives to traditional pastry options made with refined white flour. Whole wheat flour imparts a nuttier, earthier flavor to pastries, which appeals to those who enjoy a more complex taste profile in their baked goods. Moreover, whole wheat flour retains more of the grain's natural nutrients, making pastries a more nutritious choice when compared to their white flour counterparts. The increasing preference for health-conscious foods, combined with the growing trend of reducing refined sugar and carbohydrates in diets, is driving the use of whole wheat flour in various pastry applications such as croissants, Danish pastries, and puff pastries.<p>The integration of whole wheat flour into pastries not only aligns with nutritional trends but also caters to the growing consumer demand for gluten-free, high-fiber, and low-sugar products. As people become more aware of the health benefits of whole grains, manufacturers are focusing on creating pastries that offer both indulgence and health benefits, using whole wheat flour as a key ingredient. As the global market for pastries continues to evolve, the adoption of whole wheat flour is expected to increase as part of a broader push for cleaner, healthier, and more sustainable baked goods.<h3>Cakes</h3><p>Whole wheat flour has found a niche in the cake-making industry, with an increasing number of consumers seeking healthier, whole-grain alternatives to traditional cakes made with refined flour. The use of whole wheat flour in cakes contributes to a more complex flavor profile, as well as a higher nutritional value, particularly in terms of fiber content. This is especially appealing to health-conscious individuals who want to indulge in a sweet treat without compromising on their dietary goals. Whole wheat cakes can be found in various forms, including carrot cakes, banana bread cakes, and other variations that combine the bene